hydra-llm (0.2.5-1) unstable; urgency=low

  * Engine rebuilds are now automatic across `apt upgrade` and `apt
    install --reinstall` (and downgrades). When a hydra-llm release
    bumps the pinned llama.cpp ref, the postinst notices the mismatch
    between the Dockerfile's ref and the LABEL baked into the user's
    existing engine image, and rebuilds the image right then. No
    extra `hydra-llm setup --rebuild` step required for a normal
    upgrade.
  * Both Dockerfiles now carry `LABEL llama_cpp_ref="${LLAMA_CPP_REF}"`
    so the postinst can read what the running image was built from.
  * Postinst rebuild is non-fatal: if `docker build` fails (network
    blip, daemon down, etc.) the previous image continues to work and
    we point the user at /var/log/hydra-llm-engine-rebuild.log plus
    `hydra-llm setup --rebuild` for a manual retry.
  * Embedder sidecars now auto-recover from corrupt GGUFs. When
    llama-server aborts at gguf_init_from_file (the canonical
    GGML_ASSERT(!key.empty()) signature, or other GGUF parser crash),
    hydra detects the failure in the container logs, deletes the
    local GGUF, re-downloads from the catalog URL, and retries once.
    Removes the need for users to remember `hydra-llm rag download
    <id> --force` after a partial download.
  * README and project page gained "Engine updates and pinning" plus
    "Embedder auto-recover" sections explaining both behaviors.

