hydra-llm (0.2.3-1) unstable; urgency=low

  * Quality-of-life pass on the chat and rag-setup flows after first
    real-user friction.
  * `hydra-llm chat` (no alias) now resolves smartly:
    - exactly one model running -> attach silently and announce which
    - several running -> list with port numbers, prompt for a number
    - none running but exactly one downloaded -> auto-attach (chat
      path will start it)
    - none running, several downloaded -> list with size, prompt
    - nothing downloaded -> list-online hint and exit
    The alias positional is now optional.
  * Default chat session file is now scoped to (cwd, alias) instead
    of a single global ~/.local/state/hydra-llm/sessions/default.json.
    Previously a chat in folder A would resume history from folder B
    (or worse: from a smoke test on another machine if the state dir
    was reused). New default path:
        ~/.local/state/hydra-llm/sessions/<sha1(cwd)[:12]>-<alias>.json
    Existing flags still work: --session foo for cross-folder global
    sessions, ./chat.json positional for arbitrary paths.
  * `hydra-llm rag setup` (single mode) presents a numbered menu when
    the recommended embedder for the user's tier is not installed but
    others are. Previously setup ignored already-installed embedders
    and pushed the user into a 2.5 GB download. Now:
        1. Download recommended (<id>, <size> GB)
        2. Use already-installed <id> (<kind>)         per installed
        N. Pick a different embedder from the catalog
        N+1. Cancel; do nothing
    Picking option 2 writes rag.default_code_embedder + default_prose_
    embedder so subsequent `hydra-llm index` calls auto-pick it.
  * `rag setup` output explains, in plain English, what dual-index
    mode is, why most users should not enable it, how to switch it on
    later, and that switching modes requires re-indexing existing
    folders. The text reads like a person wrote it.
  * README + project page gain a "What is an embedder" subsection and
    a "Single-embedder vs dual-index mode" subsection. The dual-mode
    trade-off is named honestly. The walk-through example shows the
    new numbered menu instead of the obsolete "Download both? [Y/n]".

